The Rivers State Commissioner for Information and Communications, Pastor Paulinus Nsirim, has warned civile servants in the state against engaging in rumour mongering, back-bitting and gossips. Nsirim, who gave the warning during his maiden meeting with staff of the Ministry of Information and Communications in Port Harcourt, described rumour mongering, back-bitting and gossips, as as little forces that spoils the vines. He asked staff of the Ministry to thank the Rivers State Governor, Chief Nyesom Wike for finding a member of the Ministry worthy to be promoted from Permanent Secretary to Commissioner for Information and Communications. The Commissioner emphasised that for the first time in the history of the State, the Ministry of Information and Communications is producing a Permanent Secretary that transformed into commissioner. Nsirim urged all staff of the Ministry to sustain the tempo they gave him seven months ago during the campaign on #OurStateOurResponsibility, adding that they should not do anything to let down Wike, who decided to bring out a Commissioner among them. He charged staff of the Ministry on the need for recreation through personal development, noting that he creates a niche for himself which has propelled him to where he is today. Nsirim stated that it is the grace of God that brought about the promotion, reiterating that he is trophy of grace, who worked assiduously for the pursuit of excellence and professionalism. He maintained however, that grace cannot work for anyone that is indolent and harbinger of bad news, remarking that staff of the Ministry should make themselves productive and more relevant in their various fields of endeavour. The Commissioner said: “Those that love excellence and hard work are those that will be my friends, I will not tolerate disrespect and indiscipline.”